Design correction — Phase 1 data fetching uses WebSocket API not REST (Sections 5, 17.2, 17.3):
The design currently says Phase 1 uses the HA REST API to pull device and capability data. This is incorrect. The WebSocket API must be used instead for the following reasons:
The WebSocket API has specific commands the REST API does not have that PistonCore requires:

get_triggers_for_target — all valid triggers for a specific device
get_conditions_for_target — all valid conditions for a specific device
get_services_for_target — all valid services for a specific device
config/entity_registry/list_for_display — optimized entity list for UI display

These are the exact commands the capability-driven wizard depends on. Without them PistonCore cannot populate the wizard dropdowns correctly from live HA data.
Correct design: PistonCore opens a WebSocket connection to HA using the long-lived access token on first launch and keeps it open during the session. All device, entity, capability, trigger, condition, and service data is fetched via WebSocket. The REST API is used only for simple one-off calls that don't require a persistent connection such as automation/reload.
Update all references to "HA REST API" in Phase 1 setup (Section 17.2) to "HA WebSocket API." Update Section 5 device model accordingly. The long-lived access token works for both — no change to setup flow required.
Note 1 — Dry Run for PyScript (Item 3):
The dry run / test feature for PyScript pistons is technically risky. Intercepting HA service calls inside a running PyScript file without actually executing them has no clean native mechanism.
Decision: Do not attempt a PyScript dry run that intercepts service calls. Instead:

For YAML pistons: dry run is fully supported — show what would be called without calling it
For PyScript pistons: dry run executes the logic but skips all service calls by wrapping them in a dry-run flag that the compiled template checks. If this proves too complex or unreliable during implementation, fall back to: PyScript test mode fires the piston live with a clear warning "This will execute real actions on your devices." No silent fake dry run.
Document this difference clearly in the UI — YAML test shows a preview, PyScript test is a live fire with warning.
Add to next session agenda: developer to assess whether dry-run flag approach is viable before committing to it.


