Note 3 — Call Another Piston (Item 5):
The "call another piston" statement type has a hidden technical problem. For PyScript pistons calling other PyScript pistons this is manageable. For YAML pistons there is no native way to trigger another automation and wait for it to finish — HA can fire an event that triggers another automation but cannot wait for its completion.
Decision:

PyScript → PyScript: supported, implement cleanly
YAML → YAML: supported as fire-and-forget only — triggers the other piston but does not wait for it to complete. User is warned of this limitation in the wizard when they add this statement to a simple piston
YAML → PyScript or mixed: if a user's piston needs to call another piston and wait, this forces conversion to PyScript. The conversion prompt applies here
Add a clear note in the wizard: "Calling another piston from a Simple piston will trigger it but will not wait for it to finish. Switch to Advanced mode if you need to wait for the called piston to complete."


Note 4 — Piston Run Status Reporting (Item 6):
The design says the companion reports piston run status back to PistonCore but never defines how. Compiled pistons run independently inside HA — PistonCore has no direct visibility into their execution.
Decision: Keep it simple and avoid risky custom mechanisms. Use what HA already provides:

Each compiled piston (both YAML and PyScript) fires a standard HA event at completion — success or failure — using HA's built-in hass.bus.fire in PyScript or event: in YAML
The companion listens for these events via its own WebSocket subscription to HA
When it receives a PistonCore event, it relays the run status to the PistonCore Docker via the existing WebSocket connection
The run log in PistonCore updates from this data
This uses only standard HA event mechanisms — no custom hacks, no fragile workarounds
